Author: LittlestAnt#3124
Content:
@Dragonoisus Can you enable comments? There's a lot I want to say. It's definitely a good start for a first year though. Here's some general comments - 

1. Shorten it to 1 page. This was really surprising to me cause normally the problem with first years is that you all can't reach 1 page in length. 4 pages of experience is impressive! But definitely shorten it to one page. Recruiters want you to be concise and only focus on the best experiences .The general rule is 1 page per 10 years of experience.

2.  As for things to remove - Remove descriptions of each of the places. Remove the paragraphs talking about what you learned. Put those in bullet points and really target your achievements.

3. Remove references. CS companies almost never want them.

Author: LittlestAnt#3124
Content: Also, I remember that you told me you're working on video games? Put those as projects on your resume

Author: LittlestAnt#3124
Content: Since you don't have cs internship experience yet, you can supplement your resume with projects

Author: Snu#0167
Content:
- CS Internships don't really need objectives
- You don't need to directly list your address
-  Spacing, there's a lot of white space near the end, but it's more compact in the beginning

Author: Simon Fong#7930
Content:
@falafel72 
You don't need your address/city.
Linkedin url seems a little weird under your name on its own. Keep it along with your other contact info.
Use bullet points instead of paragraphs. Try to keep them about a line each.
Your right column seems pretty cramped. Consider doing a single column.
Work Experience should be above projects because getting paid to do work looks better.
For your projects you have . a '-' so you can have a your role after it, but for Quad and E4E, it's just blank after the '-'.
This is a small nit, but the url's look a little weird all caps, it feels like it's yelling at me

Author: Simon Fong#7930
Content:
For project drive, use 'autonomously' instead of 'automatically'
I don't you need this 'without the use of 3rd party libraries like DonkeyCar.' 
User able -> User is able

Author: LittlestAnt#3124
Content:
@StoneT2000 Damn this resume is really impressive.

First off, keep your resume down to one page. I think the highlights section is not necessary (recruiters don't care for it). Also try to shorten your description for your internship to just a few lines (At least trim it in half but I would recommend removing at least 2/3).

I would make some of your lines shorter as well. Try to keep everything in concise bullet points. Remember that recruiters go through thousands of resumes a day. Your goal is to make every single word on your resume meaningful so even when recruiters are skimming through it, they'll feel that you're a good candidate.

Additionally, I would increase the font size. Again, your goal is to make your resume easy to read for a recruiter who has gone through thousands of these and whose eyes are probably burning up by the time they get to yours.

I personally recommend the order experience / education --> projects --> awards --> skills. I think recruiters care most about experience and check for skills last.

Everything else is great. You have a tremendous amount of experience and this is a very strong resume for a first year. As you progress through college, shift out some of your high school experience with college experience.

Also, I would recommend bringing your resume to the career fair on October 2nd. I recommend asking recruiters to critique your resume. We're also hosting a resume workshop the Monday before (September 30).

Author: LittlestAnt#3124
Content:
@nibnalin 

I love your resume design, I've seen the template a lot amongst graphic designers. Unfortunately, while it looks nice, software engineering recruiters want a lot more information. I would expand on the descriptions of each of your top experiences. At the very least, go more into detail about your experience at Wolfram.

It's also recommended to format your descriptions in the form of bullet points (It's ugly having dots all over your resume, I know) in order to help recruiters get through your resume faster. They're spending just a few seconds on your resume and so it's important to make it as readable as possible, even if it sacrifices some of the aesthetic.

I also highly recommend having a single column format resume in order to pass Applicant Tracking Software. Feel free to bring fancy looking resumes to career fairs and recruiting events next week though

Content:
Another thing I would do, would be to use more strong words in your resume. You did a lot of impressive things. You should display them in a way that does yourself justice. 
Like ‚Äúplanned‚Äù could be ‚Äúcoordinated.‚Äù Instead of saying you ‚Äúcollaborated with a team,‚Äù you can say you ‚ÄúBuilt.‚Äù Wording does matter. If you do it, make sure you take the credit. Even if you worked in a team, saying you did something, doesn‚Äôt mean you‚Äôre not giving your team credit for things. As a data scientist who works in teams, I would say things like ‚ÄúCreated algorithm for anomaly detection of physicians by over prescription.‚Äù I definitely had help from others. That doesn‚Äôt mean I have to say I worked in a team because it‚Äôs kind of assumed if I am in a company, or am a student/intern that I didn‚Äôt do things alone.

Content: @FirstPersonMuffin I think the contents of your resume are quite solid! But in terms of the look, I would actually fix your left column so that there's more space in the middle between the left and right side? To me it feels too cluttered so fixing the margins would definitely help! I'd also advise you to take out the high school coursework in your resume since I feel that you already have a lot of relevant experience that having the high school courses wouldn't rly help. But for now keeping the high school leadership is solid. Also, I wouldn't even put "First-Year Plan". If you just list the courses it'll be fine.

Author: Daniel Truong#0760
Content: @sencho In terms of wording, I would avoid using the phrase "Be able to" and use more action verbs. If you also find that in the future you are running out of space, I'd recommend getting rid of the descriptions about what the company or institution you've worked for does since I feel that it's not really necessary. But for now, I'd say to fix the spacing so that there's more space between the bolded title and the description so that it's more readable. In terms of content, I'd also add the classes you are planning to take under education (i like that you just put 4.0 btw lmaoo). Also I'd get rid of the line that says "I create beautiful ...". But yeah for the most part the content is good! Just a couple of minor tweeks should help it alot

- Include actual usernames for LinkedIn and GitHub, not just links. Offline, they won't be able to click on the links and online, ATS won't pull it out. Also some people might not realize it's clickable

For Education
- I would remove "2nd year undergrad with junior standing" Just expected graduation date is good enough
- Currently taking and relevant courses taken can be combined into one "Relevant Courses" section

For Experience
- Overall good descriptions for Google CSSI. Perhaps bold a few less words though, it's a bit distracting rather than emphasizing

For Technical Projects
- The link for B/lend isn't going to be available for most recruiters, it might help more if you take a shortened URL and place it on the side.
- Overall projects and descriptions are good!

For right column
- I personally recommend a single column format because it's easier to read for recruiters and it passes through ATS more. However, it's up to you because I do know two columns look nicer so you can take the risk.

Everything else looks good! Solid resume so far!

Content:
@xyzmonk101 Overall really solid resume!

- For experience, As nibnalin said, change written to wrote. Besides that, your descriptions are solid. Perhaps include a bit more technologies in them. For example, did you use EagleCAD, Altrium to make PCBs or what languages did you use to write your scripts in line 3 (Python, Bash etc, i'm guessing implied BASH bc line 2)

- For education, I would remove relevant coursework until you take more impactful classes. Right now, saying you've only taken Java I hurts more than it helps. It shows the recruiter you aren't in your upper div classes yet and you're gonna want to hide that.

- For projects, and experience too, I would avoid repeating developed and created on repeat. Seek other words that really describe your impact. Words like collaborated in a team, or designed to show that you not only created it but you put effort into laying out how it SHOULD be built add quite a lot!

Author: LittlestAnt#3124
Content:
-----
@British Yeri 
- For education, remove your intro classes. Only put the classes that matter the most for the career you're looking at. Overtime, as you gain more experience, you can remove more and more coursework since coursework is generally seen as just resume filler.

- For experience, add more info about SPIS! I'm not quite sure what the program entails but I recommend focusing more on what you built because it, in turn, showcases what you learned. For example, what technologies did you use to make your letter recognition program. What programming language? Scikit learn, tensorflow? You can include these!

- Do not separate technical projects and academic projects. Just put them together. Also, don't focus on what the project is, focus on what you did for the project instead. What technologies did you use? What languages? How much time did you build it in? How many people did you work on it with? How efficient is it? Basically, aim to answer the question "What did I do?" vs "What is the project?".

- For skills, do not rank your skills! I know the Career Center advises to do this but it doesn't apply to tech. Don't rank your skills but just list them instead. The interviewer will be the best judge of your skills. If you put basic / proficient instead of advanced it could hurt you because you are saying you aren't super confident about your skills but if you put advanced and you end up not being as good as they expect in your interview, they would think you were lying. Just list your skills especially since each company has different standards.

- Overall, you're almost there. Get a few more projects on your resume and rewrite some descriptions. Trust me, your resume is A LOT better than mine was when I was a second year at this time so feel good about yourself but keep on revising it!

Author: Solaratoz#6571

Author: LittlestAnt#3124
Content:
Hi @Solaratoz!

First off, your title doesn't make it very clear that you're studying Computer Engineering and that you're Class of 2023 at UCSD. I would place both of those underneath UC San Diego.

Secondly, go for descriptions in the form of bullet points! 

Also increase your font size. Your goal is to make your resume as easy to read for your recruiter as possible! This will also help fill up some blank space. I think the general rule is minimum 10.5 font.

Your devpost and github images are kind of blurry. If you can, try to also color them so they're thematically the same as your other icons. It creates more consistency!

Once you change your descriptions to bullet points, feel free to send it again. I love that your current descriptions talk about what you did and what you accomplished! Include more numbers if you can and try to be more precise in your descriptions (what technologies did you use, how many people were on your team, etc)

Besides that, this is a really good resume for some one this early in college! Just continue building more projects (Looks like you finished one at SD Hacks) and continue working hard.

@Solaratoz

Author: LittlestAnt#3124
Content:
@hexalellogram 
This is looking pretty solid so far! 

- Put college above high school! They prefer everything in chronological order from most to least recent. Same goes with experience

- Also, remove "unpaid" from your bullet point. Unpaid does nothing but hurt your resume, you don't need to tell them how much you're getting paid.

- Like I said with Quoc, I think you should split your descriptions up into bullet points. Also, include more bullet points as well! Go into further detail about your experience!

- In continuation of the above point, I would actually remove some activities and projects that you don't care as much about so that you have space to elaborate on your more significant experiences. Remember, it's not about the quantity of your experiences but about the quality so really showcase that!

- Awards look good!

- Skills look good, I would remove the word "basic" preceding Python and Javascript because that does nothing but hurt you

ALSO, we're the Association for Computing Machinery not OF (I used to get it mixed up a lot too and I think of sounds a lot better than for too)

I can't really say much about your essays, I think they're solid! Feel free to break the rules of a traditional essay though and try to showcase your personality as best you can! Google is a company that follows pretty much no rules and so don't worry too much about being super formal, or even serious, in your writing.

Overall, resume is good. I would just add more details where you can!

Author: riku#6996
Content:
@sw4nky I'm not Simon, but I have a similar work history to him (interned at FB, Disney, ServiceNow, and Nintendo as SWE) as a Cog Sci major, so I can maybe answer your question:

It really only affected me initially when I didn't have any job history - there were a couple companies that turned me down on the basis of not being computer science. Once I got my first internship it was pretty smooth sailing afterwards (from 450 applications with 6 interviews to 10 applications with 10 interviews); recruiters saw "cog sci" and were like "oh hey that's neat".

Author: Simon Fong#7930
Content:
@sw4nky Woops, yeah I don't have discord notifications on lol
It's pretty common for EE's to switch into software, some people for example:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_Bezos
Gusto Founder: https://www.linkedin.com/in/tomerlondon/
Gusto Founder: https://www.linkedin.com/in/edawerd/
Shift Software Engineer: https://www.linkedin.com/in/chen-zhu-0908/
UCSD Alumni (One of my mentors): https://www.linkedin.com/in/willchenyh/
Random Google person I met, but I forgot her name lol

For most large companies (FAANG), they likely won't care too much about difference between EE and CS. Although, I've heard smaller companies might discriminate more because they don't want to risk as much resources on a candidate.

But that mostly only matters for the beginning, like @riku  said. After your first internship, your degree will matter less.

During interviews if they ask "Tell me about yourself", I do mention my degree and explain my path on why I chose software (Less than 10 secs).

The main disadvantage has been not knowing things that CS students are supposed to know by the time they graduate. For example:
- Google Interview asked a Dynamic Programming question and I never learned it, so I failed that one
- Atlassian Interview asked a multithreading question with locks, and I scraped by using random stuff I read before
- During an internship, they talked about OS concepts which I didn't understand, so I had to look it up

For most of these though, I just needed to do some self-learning to get past it

Author: BarackGrande#3968
Content: just a quick rant, I think tech interviews are more about answering easy/medium-difficulty questions correctly and quickly rather than solving really hard ones

Author: BarackGrande#3968
Content: The interviewers won't be as disappointed if you fail on a hard q. (but you show your willingness to learn), but if you fail on a medium/easy difficulty question then it really shows a lack of preparation

Author: sw4nky#8532

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: First thing off the bat is definitely limit it to one page, one side

Content: Interests section - not 100% necessary imo especially when you are strained for space

Content: im going to direct you to http://acmurl.com/resumetips which is the evaluation sheet we used last week at the resume critique event

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: Definitely cut the spacing down so you can squeeze more things onto the page, since you're going over as is

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: skills - problem solving and collaboration... that's kind of assumed and not necessary to list on a resume

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content:
keep each of your bullets to about one line or so, and combine the shorter bullets into one line (for example under your "Fundraising Lead" entry:
- pitched fundraising proposal to local community, raising $5,000 for materials

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: and the 'analyzed data to improve my outcomes" is really just generic sounding filler. if you want to expand on that with some specifics, feel free to do so (like did you use some sort of specific data analysis tool or something, especially since your major is data science), otherwise just remove that bullet

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: also it might be advisable to list some relevant coursework that you've taken, but if all of your courses are introductory level courses, keep it to just one or two so you don't use too much space

Author: hexalellogram#1647
Content: Overall, your resume needs to be shorter and more compact and you need need need to fit it onto one page. Editing your bullets to condense things down as well as trimming your spacing will help, but if necessary you may need to choose one or two positions to remove if you can't fit everything (my personal pick to remove would be the fundraising lead position, but that is your call to make)

Author: Hairy Otter#4797
Content:
-Rather than having a bullet point for each of your projects/experience, I would say separate each of those into their own little list of bullet points. It's hard to read it when it's in paragraph style
-Move your education to the top, and put your GPA if it's roughly around 3.5+
-Make sure you can talk about all of the skills and qualifications you listed in an interview setting, otherwise remove some of it
-I've heard mixed opinions about summaries, since you really can just say your summary verbally as your elevator pitch, rather than take up space on your resume to do it

Author: Jacinth G | MEMEber at Large#1094
Content: I see, so separate experiences into bullet points instead of paragraphs?

Author: riku#6996
Content: Absolutely, your resume is very hard to read in its current formatting, and when you consider many recruiters only have seconds to review your resume, they won't bother with anything they can't read.

Author: rin#0388
Content:
I don't see the point of the title: Computer Engineering **Intern**. The recruiter or whoever looks at your resume knows what position you are applying to. I recommend to remove the "Summary Of Qualification" header, but you can still have a skills header above your skills.

You don't need to emphasize Vi, Vim, gVim; Just list one that you primary use.
It's cool to flex to people that you use Vi, although I don't believe you should mention it in your summary or multiple times.

- Negative Space on your resume matters.
- Bullet point your significances or accomplishments for your Experience/Project instead of paragraph form. Most recruiters don't actually read your resume, they just scan through it.

Author: Hairy Otter#4797
Content:
-Too much whitespace on the edges, make your margins smaller and make your font bigger
-Usually you shouldn't need to put your full address on your resume (privacy concerns)
-Having a summary at the top is kinda outdated, especially since you can verbally give it in your elevator pitch
-A nitpicky thing, but I usually see dates for experiences on the right side of the resume instead of the left
-Phase out your high school stuff asap, it's not relevant when you're in college
-Put your college education at the top of your resume instead of the bottom so recruiters can quickly see what year you are (also put your expected graduation year)
-I'd recommend a section for your extracurriculars/leadership positions in college, so that you can show your other experiences as well as anything interesting that might catch recruiters' eyes and make you easier to remember
